HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1487
By Keisling
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Michael "Mike" Earl
Tatum.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Michael "Mike" Earl Tatum; and
WHEREAS, Mike Tatum was an exemplary public servant and consummate professional
who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in numerous
capacities; and
WHEREAS, born in Davidson County on February 18, 1944, Mr. Tatum was the son of
Bob and Hazel Sexton Tatum; and
WHEREAS, Mike Tatum lived a life defined by selfless service, principled leadership,
and a deep, abiding commitment to both his community and his faith; and
WHEREAS, early in his professional career, Mr. Tatum served with acumen and alacrity
as both teacher and principal at Westside Elementary School, where he worked tirelessly to lay
a strong and lasting foundation for generations of learners; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Tatum was proud to serve Macon County High School as vice principal,
in which role he demonstrated a deep passion for shaping young lives both inside and outside
the classroom; as a basketball and baseball coach, he inspired his student athletes to strive for
excellence in academics and athletics alike; and
WHEREAS, following his distinguished career in education, Mike Tatum took a much-
deserved retirement from the Macon County Board of Education, leaving behind a legacy of
integrity, mentorship, and unwavering dedication to his students and colleagues alike; and
HJR1487
018203
- 1 -

WHEREAS, a highly respected member of his community, Mr. Tatum was a member of
the Macon County Retired Teachers Association, the Lions Club, and the Macon County Farm
Bureau Board of Directors; and
WHEREAS, Mike Tatum was also devoted to his family and always endeavored to
remain true to family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, he will be sadly missed but fondly remembered by his beloved wife of fifty-
seven years, Elaine Taylor Tatum; his children, LaDonna (Paul) Little and Michael (YongOk)
Tatum; his grandchildren, Jonathan (Brittany) Swaffer, Angela Tatum, and Justin Tatum; his
great-grandchildren, Landon Swaffer and Harley Marlow; his step-grandchildren, Leah (David)
Brackin, Pauline (Brandon) Coyne, and Jacob Little; three step-great-grandchildren; his brother,
Robert "Pat" (Lila) Tatum; his sisters-in-law, Ann Driver and Ruth Gregory; and a host of nieces
and nephews; and
WHEREAS, in addition to his parents, Mr. Tatum was preceded in death by his brother,
Phillip Tatum; and
WHEREAS, Mike Tatum was wholly dedicated to his faith, and for forty-nine years, he
was a senior adult Sunday School teacher at Lafayette Missionary Baptist Church, guiding
others with his wisdom, compassion, and a steadfast devotion to God's Word; he was also a
member of Meadorville Missionary Baptist Church; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Tatum was a compassionate and faithful soul who greatly impacted the
lives of those who were blessed to know him, and he leaves behind an indelible legacy of
integrity and probity in public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and
dedication in all his chosen endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to
remember the bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
- 2 - 018203

BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Michael "Mike" Earl Tatum, reflecting fondly upon
his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage
and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Tatum.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
